						<!-- firstHeading -->
			<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en"><span dir="auto"><i>Natural History</i> (Pliny)</span></h1>
			<!-- /firstHeading -->
			<!-- bodyContent -->
			<div id="bodyContent">
								<!-- tagline -->
				<div id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
				<!-- /tagline -->
								<!-- subtitle -->
				<div id="contentSub">  (Redirected from <a href="../../w/index-title=Naturalis_Historia&redirect=no.php.html" title="Naturalis Historia">Naturalis Historia</a>)</div>
				<!-- /subtitle -->
																<!-- jumpto -->
				<div id="jump-to-nav" class="mw-jump">
					Jump to:					<a href="#mw-head">navigation</a>, 					<a href="#p-search">search</a>
				</div>
				<!-- /jumpto -->
								<!-- bodycontent -->
				<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Naturalishistoria.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/67/Naturalishistoria.jpg/220px-Naturalishistoria.jpg" width="220" height="371" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/67/Naturalishistoria.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/67/Naturalishistoria.jpg 2x" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Naturalishistoria.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="http://bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf7/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
<i>Naturalis Historia</i>, 1669 edition, title page. The title at the top reads: "Volume I of the <i>Natural History</i> of Gaius Plinius Secundus."</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The <i><b>Natural History</b></i> (<a href="Latin_language" title="Latin language" class="mw-redirect">Latin</a>: <span lang="la" xml:lang="la"><i>Naturalis Historia</i></span>) is an encyclopedia published <a href="Circa" title="Circa">circa</a> AD&#160;77–79 by <a href="Pliny_the_Elder" title="Pliny the Elder">Pliny the Elder</a>. It is one of the largest single works to have survived from the <a href="Roman_Empire" title="Roman Empire">Roman Empire</a> to the modern day and purports to cover all ancient knowledge.</p>
<p>The work became a model for all later encyclopedias in terms of the breadth of subject matter examined, the need to reference original authors, and a comprehensive <a href="Index_(publishing)" title="Index (publishing)">index</a> of the contents. The work is dedicated to the emperor <a href="Titus" title="Titus">Titus</a>, son of Pliny's close friend, the emperor <a href="Vespasian" title="Vespasian">Vespasian</a>, in the first year of Titus's reign. It is the only work by Pliny to have survived and the last that he published, lacking a final revision at the time of <a href="Pliny_the_Elder#Death" title="Pliny the Elder">his death</a> during the <a href="Vesuvius#Eruption_of_AD_79" title="Vesuvius" class="mw-redirect">AD&#160;79 eruption of Vesuvius</a>.</p>
